Machine Learning Project - Predicting a country's energy mix

Warning :

I created this project in 2024, during a Machine Learning class at ESILV. I uploaded it because some aspects are good, but it has some defaults. A new version is to be created and uploaded here, addressing the following issues : -French / English mixed up -Questioning and addressing the dataset building methodology -Trying to cluster the data in a more relevant way -More accurate geopolitical analysis about the different countries' characteristics (industry, ecology, etc.) The new version will also have to be shorter, containing an appendix for non-essential data.

This notebook contains all the work and analyses performed on the "World Energy Consumption" dataset. It must be ran using scikit learn version 1.5.2 and xgboost version 2.1.1.

In[]:

Stage 1 : implementation of standard solutions

1. Analysis of the data

To get the spirit of the dataset, we need to identify the features and the target columns of it. Features include country, year, iso_code, population and GDP. We could use GDP as a target and the energy productions and consumptions as features but we will do it the other way around, as we're studying energy. All remaining columns, consumptions, production, and the repartition of these per capita or per way of production, will be targets.

First, let's start with a quick quality check of the data.

In[4]:

num_distinct_countries = energy_data['country'].nunique()

Number of distinct countries: 306

Countries are a categorical variable. One-Hot Encodage is not really an option because of the number of distinct countries in the dataset. We will still keep that data in the dataset, because it can be used with embeddings or CatBoost, for example.

Let's take a look at the correlation between the variables. We will do it bit by bit, because otherwise no computer will be able to face the complexity of the correlation matrix calculation.

In[10]:
# 1. First, we'll talk a look at the correlation between consumptions to see which ones evolve together :
columns_to_keep = ['renewables_consumption', 'solar_consumption', 'wind_consumption', 'biofuel_consumption', 'hydro_consumption', 'other_renewable_consumption', 'low_carbon_consumption', 'nuclear_consumption', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'coal_consumption', 'gas_consumption', 'oil_consumption', 'primary_energy_consumption']
df=energy_data[columns_to_keep]
correlation_matrix = df.corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap="coolwarm", cbar=True)
plt.title('Matrice de Corrlation')
plt.show()

We can see that there are very strong correlations between some variables, which is quite logic : the consumption of renewable energies is closely linked to hydro and low-carbon consumptions. We can also notice that it is linked to the fossil fuel consumption ; that is logical, because the production of renewables generally doesn't lower the production of other energies ; it often only compensates for the increase in demand. This statistical review of world energy by the energy institute explains it : https://www.energyinst.org/statistical-review.

Low carbon is also closely linked to hydro, which is known to be a very clean source of energy. Primary energy is closely linked to fossil fuel, which is still logical, because oil and fossil fuels are widely used in regards to other primary energies such as wind or solar, so they account for more in the primary energies consumption numbers. Oil and gas are also closely linked to fossil fuels consumption. All of this indicate PCA will probably be very useful for this dataset, as a lot of data are closely linked. Now that we've checked these data, let's take a look at the links between economical and demographic data and energy consumption.

In[11]:
# 2. Now, let's take a look at the links between demographic, economic and energy data :
columns_to_keep = ['population', 'gdp', 'energy_per_gdp', 'electricity_demand', 'electricity_generation', 'net_elec_imports', 'renewables_consumption', 'low_carbon_consumption', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'greenhouse_gas_emissions',  'renewables_share_elec', 'renewables_share_energy']
df=energy_data[columns_to_keep]
correlation_matrix = df.corr()
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap="coolwarm", cbar=True)
plt.title('Matrice de Corrlation')
plt.show()

We can see that GDP is closely linked to energy consumption, more than population ; population seems to have a lower impact on energy consumption. This gives proof that energy is more a matter of standards of living than the number of people in concerned country.
We can notice that GDP is also closely linked to energy production : we can explain that with more developed countries needing a lot of energy as they can afford to be less efficient, their economies being based on services, and population densities being higher in those kinds of countries, which have most of the time achieved their demographical transition. Countries are also producing their energy for themselves ; countries needing to import energy or not has visibly no correlation with their consumption, population or GDP.
Despite popular belief, we can also see that countries with higher GDP are typically not "cleaner" (don't use more renewables in their energy mix) than countries with smaller economies ; that shows that it is more a matter of choice. A big or small economy has visibly no correlation with use of renewable energies.
We can also notice that countries with higher GDP also tend to have higher greenhouse gases emissions.

In[12]:
latest_data = energy_data.dropna(subset=['iso_code'])  # Keep only rows with valid ISO codes
latest_data = latest_data.sort_values('year').groupby('country').last().reset_index()

plot_data = latest_data[['country', 'population', 'gdp', 'electricity_demand']].dropna()

top_countries = plot_data.nlargest(20, 'electricity_demand')

# Crer le graphique
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
plt.scatter(
    plot_data['population'],
    plot_data['gdp'],
    s=plot_data['electricity_demand'],
    alpha=0.6,
    edgecolor="w"
)

# Prparer les tiquettes uniquement pour les 20 plus gros pays
texts = []
for i, row in top_countries.iterrows():
    texts.append(plt.text(
        row['population'],
        row['gdp'],
        row['country'],
        fontsize=9,
        alpha=0.7
    ))

# Ajuster automatiquement les positions des tiquettes
adjust_text(
    texts, 
    arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle="->", color='gray', lw=0.5)  # Ajouter des flches pour plus de clart
)

# Ajouter des labels, un titre et des chelles
plt.title("Population vs GDP, Electricity Demand as bubble size", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Population", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("GDP", fontsize=12)
plt.xscale('log')  # chelle logarithmique pour la population
plt.yscale('log')  # chelle logarithmique pour le PIB
plt.grid(alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

metrics_by_year = df.groupby('year')[[
    'population', 
    'gdp', 
    'energy_per_capita', 
    'electricity_generation', 
    'fossil_fuel_consumption', 
    'renewables_consumption'
]].sum()

# We normalize the data to compare their evolution and not their values ! 
metrics_normalized = metrics_by_year.apply(lambda x: (x - x.min()) / (x.max() - x.min()), axis=0)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(14, 8))
colors = ['blue', 'green', 'orange', 'red', 'purple', 'brown']
labels = [
    'Population', 
    'GDP', 
    'Energy Per Capita', 
    'Electricity Generation', 
    'Fossil Fuel Consumption', 
    'Renewables Consumption'
]

for column, color, label in zip(metrics_normalized.columns, colors, labels):
    ax.plot(metrics_normalized.index, metrics_normalized[column], label=label, color=color)

legend = ax.legend(loc="upper left", title="Legend", frameon=True, fancybox=True, shadow=True, borderpad=1)
legend.get_frame().set_edgecolor('black')
ax.tick_params(left=False, bottom=True, labelleft=False, labelbottom=True)
ax.set_title("Evolution of demographic and economical data through time", fontsize=14)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

def highlight_zero_and_null(val):
    if pd.isnull(val):  # Vrifier si la valeur est NaN
        return 'background-color: red'
    elif val == 0:  # Vrifier si la valeur est 0
        return 'background-color: red'
    else:
        return ''


styled_df = df.style.applymap(highlight_zero_and_null)
display(styled_df)

df_long = pd.melt(df, id_vars=['year'], var_name='Indicator', value_name='Value')
df_long = df_long.pivot(index='year', columns='Indicator', values='Value').fillna(0).reset_index()

# Prepare the data for the barplot
indicators = df_long.columns[1:]
years = df_long['year']
bar_width = 0.2
x_positions = np.arange(len(years))

# Create graphic
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
for i, indicator in enumerate(indicators):
    plt.bar(x_positions + i * bar_width, df_long[indicator], width=bar_width, label=indicator)

# Add labels
plt.xticks(x_positions + bar_width * (len(indicators) - 1) / 2, years, rotation=45)
plt.title("Evolution of Global Energetic Indicators per Year")

Looking at this, we can say that energy per capita needs raise more in industrialized regions such as Asia and South America, which provide a lot of transformed goods for the world. Needs in Europe and South America are quite high but these didn't raise since these countries went from industrial to services economies. We can notice that there is visibly no data available on electricity generation before the mid-80s, and while Asia developped very quickly and their needs raised with population and technological transformation, the other continent's need have raised more slowly. We can say the exact same thing with fossil fuels and renewables consumptions, although fossil fuel consumption seem to have slowed down in Europe and North America since about 2010.

Let's also take a look on whether or not countries will be able to use low carbon electricity and renewable energies.

In[20]:
energy_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'] = np.where(
    energy_data['electricity_generation'] == 0, 
    np.nan, 
    (energy_data['low_carbon_electricity'] / energy_data['electricity_generation']) * 100
)

# Calculate the rate of renewable energy while avoiding dividing by 0.
energy_data['renewable_energy_percentage'] = np.where(
    (energy_data['renewables_consumption'] + energy_data['fossil_fuel_consumption']) == 0,
    np.nan, 
    (energy_data['renewables_consumption'] / 
     (energy_data['renewables_consumption'] + energy_data['fossil_fuel_consumption'])) * 100
)

# Filtrate the last 10 years available for each country.
latest_years = energy_data.groupby('country')['year'].nlargest(10).reset_index(level=0)
latest_data = energy_data.merge(latest_years, on=['country', 'year'])

# Compute the average for each country on the last 10 years.
average_data = latest_data.groupby('country')[['low_carbon_electricity_percentage', 'renewable_energy_percentage']].mean()

# Sort the countries for each indicator
top_25_low_carbon = average_data[['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']].sort_values(
    by='low_carbon_electricity_percentage', ascending=False
).head(25)

top_25_renewable = average_data[['renewable_energy_percentage']].sort_values(
    by='renewable_energy_percentage', ascending=False
).head(25)


def color_percentage(val):
    if pd.isnull(val):  # Handle the NaN
        return ''
    elif val == 100:
        return 'background-color: darkgreen; color: white'
    elif val > 90:
        return 'background-color: green; color: white'
    elif val > 70:
        return 'background-color: lightgreen; color: black'
    elif val > 50:
        return 'background-color: lightblue; color: black'
    elif val > 30:
        return 'background-color: blue; color: white'
    else:
        return ''  
    
    
styled_top_25_low_carbon = top_25_low_carbon.style.applymap(color_percentage).set_caption(
    "Top 25 Countries by Average Low Carbon Electricity Percentage"
)
styled_top_25_renewable = top_25_renewable.style.applymap(color_percentage).set_caption(
    "Top 25 Countries by Average Renewable Energy Percentage"
)

display(styled_top_25_low_carbon)
display(styled_top_25_renewable)

Over the last 10 years, a lot of countries have low carbon electricity. We can try later to predict whether or not a country has low carbon electricity. Fewer countries have renewable energy.

To conclude with this part of data analysis and adaptation, we chose to not reduce, normalize or standardize the data now. We will train the models with data reduced and not reduced, thus we will see if it's more efficient to not perform these operations on this dataset using verifications. Moreover, some of these simplification options are useful only with certain algorithms, like a linear regression. We will eventually use them, but only when needed.

2. Implement solutions for each task using the algos seen in class.

We will try to predict energy consumption for the years to come, in different countries and different continents. We will also look at the ability of the country to use low carbon electricity.

First, let's look at whether or not we can predict ability of countries to get low-carbon electricity.

Let's start with defining what we call ability of countries to get low-carbon electricity. Let's take a look at the distribution of different rates of low-carbon electricity :

In[21]:
# Filtrate data to keep only countries with ISO code.
filtered_data = energy_data.dropna(subset=['iso_code'])

# Compute low-carbon electricity percentage.
filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'] = np.where(
    filtered_data['electricity_generation'] == 0, 
    np.nan, 
    (filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity'] / filtered_data['electricity_generation']) * 100)
filtered_data = filtered_data.dropna(subset=['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'])

# Create intervals for percentages
bins = [0, 30, 50, 70, 90, 100]
labels = ['0-30', '30-50', '50-70', '70-90', '90-100']

# Add a column for categories.
filtered_data['category'] = pd.cut(
    filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=True)
distribution = filtered_data['category'].value_counts(sort=False)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

In[22]:
filtered_data = energy_data.dropna(subset=['iso_code'])

filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'] = np.where(
    filtered_data['electricity_generation'] == 0, 
    np.nan, 
    (filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity'] / filtered_data['electricity_generation']) * 100)
filtered_data = filtered_data.dropna(subset=['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'])

# Identify the last 10 years with data for each country.
latest_years = filtered_data.groupby('country')['year'].nlargest(10).reset_index(level=0)

# Join to keep only the last 10 years.
latest_data = filtered_data.merge(latest_years, on=['country', 'year'])

# Compute the mean for the last 10 years for each country.
average_data = latest_data.groupby('country')['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'].mean().reset_index()

# Count the countries higher and below 50%.
total_countries = average_data['country'].nunique()
above_50 = average_data[average_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'] > 50].shape[0]
below_or_equal_50 = average_data[average_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage'] <= 50].shape[0]
above_50_percentage = (above_50 / total_countries) * 100
below_or_equal_50_percentage = (below_or_equal_50 / total_countries) * 100
print(f"Number of countries with more than 50% low-carbon electricty : {above_50} ({above_50_percentage:.2f}%)")
print(f"Number of countries with 50% or less low-carbon electricity : {below_or_equal_50} ({below_or_equal_50_percentage:.2f}%)")

We have about 35-65% ratio of countries having more than 50% low-carbon energy. That is enough to not need to balance the data. Here we are observing a small amount of data (210 countries) ; thus, Logistic Regression and Decision Tree are the better "beginner" options to try and predict whether or not a country has low carbon energy. Let's start with adding a binary column indicating "1" if the country is using more than 50% low-carbon energy, "0" if not.

A. Decision Tree

We still a relatively balanced data when we take it per country and per year instead of computing the mean for a country over the period of time. We will still be able to use solutions such as "class_weight='balanced'" or SMOTE to see if these are more efficient.

In[25]:
features = ['renewables_consumption', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'electricity_generation', 'population', 'gdp']
X = df[features]
y = df['low_carbon_binary']
# Right before we're just checking that X and y don't contain NaN !

# Divide the data in training and test ensembles.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Train a decision tree
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test ensemble.
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# Print the results
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Accuracy: 0.9024390243902439

Classification Report:
               precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.99      0.87      0.92        84
           1       0.78      0.97      0.86        39

    accuracy                           0.90       123
   macro avg       0.88      0.92      0.89       123
weighted avg       0.92      0.90      0.90       123
In[26]:
# Let's visualize the tree :
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plot_tree(clf, feature_names=features, class_names=["Not Low Carbon", "Low Carbon"], filled=True)
plt.show()

These indicate that the model predicts the correct class for most of the instances (90% of the time in total). It has a very high precision for class 0, which means that when the model predicts 0, it is almost always correct. It has a high F1-Score, indicating good precision and recall. When the model predicts 1, it is correct 78% of the time. The fact that this is also the least frequent class tells us to remain prudent, as it is worse than the score for class 0. However, it has a very good recall, meaning that it successfully identifies most of the actual instances of 1. That's also what Weighted Average tells us : with an F1-score of 90%, the model is quite good.

All of this means that, when given renewable energy consumption, fossil fuel consumption, electricity_generation, gdp and population of a country, we can predict with a precision of about 90% whether or not it is able to use more energy from renewable sources than from fossil fuel sources.

Support for class 0 (84) being more than the double that of class 1 (39) is an imbalance. This can influence the performance metrics. Let's try to do it again, this time imbalancing data before with SMOTE :

In[27]:
features = ['renewables_consumption', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'electricity_generation', 'population', 'gdp']
X = df[features]
y = df['low_carbon_binary']

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Apply SMOTE to balance the classes in the training set.
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Print the class distribution before and after SMOTE.
print("Class distribution before SMOTE :")
print(y_train.value_counts())
print("\nClass distribution after SMOTE :")
print(pd.Series(y_train_resampled).value_counts())

clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

low_carbon_binary

Accuracy: 0.8943089430894309

               precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.99      0.86      0.92        84

    accuracy                           0.89       123
   macro avg       0.87      0.92      0.89       123
weighted avg       0.91      0.89      0.90       123

After SMOTE, all metrics are either slightly decreased or unchanged. A slight drop in accuracy is expected because SMOTE modifies the training data, prioritizing class balance over the overall accuracy. Metrics for class 0 remain stable, with only a minor decrease in recall (from 87% to 86%), reflecting that the model still performs well for the majority class. Metrics for class 1 remained stable as well, as recall remains very high (97%), indicating that the model continues to identify most positive cases. Precision dropped slightly (from 78% to 76%), showing a marginal increase in false positives for class 1. SMOTE did not give results that were way worse, but it is of better use in models with low recall for the minority class. Here, recall for class 1 was already high. We can explain that with the strong correlation between some of the variables and the target, low_carbon, as shown previously in the correlation matrix.

We can still try again to make it better using automatic class weight balancing :

In[28]:
clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=5, class_weight='balanced', random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test ensemble
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# Print the results
print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

B. Logistic Regression

In[30]:

This model gives an accuracy of 68%. However, this is high accuracy is misleading because it has not predicted any instance of the class 1. Let's try to adjust the threshold to get better results. Then we'll try to use SMOTE and the class balance to see if it gives better results.

In[31]:
# Predict probabilities
y_prob = clf.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# Adjust threshold
threshold = 0.3
y_pred_adjusted = (y_prob >= threshold).astype(int)

# Evaluate with the adjusted threshold
print("Adjusted Classification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred_adjusted))

adjusted_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_adjusted)
print(f"Adjusted Accuracy (Threshold = {threshold}): {adjusted_accuracy:.4f}")

   macro avg       0.69      0.61      0.46       123
weighted avg       0.80      0.47      0.42       123

Adjusted Accuracy (Threshold = 0.3): 0.4715

With adjusted threshold, the model manages to predict correctly a few instances of the class 1. However, its accuracy is very bad, 0.439. This means it will predict the wrong instance more than one time out of two. Moreover, it's still quite bad for class 1 specifically (it gets it right one time out of 36). Let's see how the model does with SMOTE and balanced class weight.

Using SMOTE gives the exact same results as without it. The synthetic samples created by SMOTE are not improving the model's ability to distinguish between two classes. Logistic Regression assumes a linear relationship between the features and the log_odds of the target class ; this might be why it doesn't work. Some features, like GDP, population, or even gross fossil fuel consumption, can have a non-linear relationship to whether or not they use more than 50% low-carbon energy. We can still try to see if the results are better with balancing class weights.

The report is still bad ; the model never predicts correctly the class 1. We can say that Logistic Regression is useless to predict whether or not a country has low-carbon electricity, because although it has a correlation to the feature, this does not mean there is a direct linear relationship.

We can conclude that a country's ability to have low-carbon electricity is predictable using their behavior towards renewables and fossil fuel consumption, their electricity production, and their population and GDP. But these are not linear relationships, so we can analyze and break down correlations using a Decision Tree but not a Logistic Regression.

And now, let's look at whether or not we can predict the numbers for electricity, renewable energy or fossil fuel production :

We will use Linear Regression, as it's the most simple and often used way to predict numbers. First, we need to identify which variables we will use as features.

features = [ 'primary_energy_consumption', 'greenhouse_gas_emissions', 'gdp', 'low_carbon_electricity', 'low_carbon_electricity', 'low_carbon_consumption', 'hydro_electricity', 'oil_consumption', 'renewables_consumption', 'renewables_electricity', 'coal_electricity', 'hydro_consumption', 'gas_consumption', 'gas_electricity', 'biofuel_electricity', 'gas_production', 'other_renewable_exc_biofuel_electricity']

Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 0.0853
Mean Squared Error (MSE): 0.0445
R^2 Score: 1.0000

An R score of 1.0000 means the model fits the data perfectly. MSE and MAE are very small, so the predictions are extremely close to actual values. MSE penalizes larger errors more than MAE. This means there are no large deviations in predictions. We can conclude that, if we have all of this data and need to predict a country's electricity generation, we're able to do it very well !

It is probable that if we want to predict electricity generation, we wouldn't have any electricity data, even about specific productions such as low_carbon_electricity or ydro_electricity. Let's try without any electricity data, using only the correlation with other data !

Here, we have a R score of 0.9999, which means the model is a nearly perfect fit, only a tiny portion of the variability is unexplained. We have a MAE of 9.9906, which is acceptable since the electricity_generation variable ranges from 0 to 10000. We have a MSE of 325, which means we might have a few predictions with larger-than-average errors.

Let's check that we didn't overfit the model.

In[42]:

Cross-Validation R Scores: [0.99850604 0.99343825 0.99404491 0.99700929 0.9994315 ]
Mean CV R: 0.9965

R scores are still OK. It is likely that the model is good and there is no overfitting. Let's still see if we can enhance the model with PCA, since a lot of data are correlated.

In[43]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_scaled, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(n_components=0.95)  # Retain 95% of the variance
X_train_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_pca = pca.transform(X_test)

# Train a regression model on PCA-transformed data
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train_pca, y_train)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_pca)

# Evaluate the model
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.4f}")
print(f"R^2 Score: {r2:.4f}")

# Check the explained variance ratio
print(f"Explained Variance Ratio: {pca.explained_variance_ratio_}")
print(f"Number of Components: {pca.n_components_}")

Mean Absolute Error (MAE): 82.5298
Mean Squared Error (MSE): 27618.5235
R^2 Score: 0.9953
Explained Variance Ratio: [0.89373586 0.06773216]
Number of Components: 2

We have a worse R score, and much worse MAE and MSE. As we have established previously, it is probable that previous model is better, that there is no overfitting, and PCA is not really relevant. If we need to establish a countries' electricty production based on other energetic data, we're likely to be able to get a good estimation using the previously trained Linear Regression.

Stage 2 : Improving the standard solution

We previously established that we can manage to make good predictions for a country's electricity production using data such as their GDP, greenhouse gas emissions, fossil fuel consumption, etc. Let's start this stage 2 with actually predicting target data using the features.

We can see that we are able to predit good enough results for energy consumption of some countries, based on other energy data. Now, to be able to improve our solution, we will try to check out other features, as we were nearly able to predict with 100% the previous target features. We can notice that we never used the year, but it could be very interesting to use it as a feature ; this way, we might be able to predict the energy data for a country for the years to come. We will also try to use more advanced versions of the preivously used algorithms. Concretely, we will try to predict the probability for a country to have more than 90% low-carbon electricity. We will also check to the probability to get more than 50% renewables share in electricity, because the method will be different, as there is a major difference in the repartitions for those conditions. We will also try to give more importance to the date variable, and see if in addition to predicting some data using other data for a country, we can predict data for for the years to come.

Predicting the ability of countries to get >50% share in electricity

In[50]:
smote = SMOTE(random_state=7)
X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

We'll start with a simple one, the Voting Classifier with soft voting, based upon probability-based aggregation :

In[53]:
xgb = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, random_state=42)
xgb.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Create a voting classifier
voting_model = VotingClassifier(estimators=[
    ('lr', logistic_model),
    ('rf', rf_model),
    ('xgb', xgb_model)
], voting='soft')

voting_model.fit(X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced)

y_pred_voting = voting_model.predict(X_test)

print("Voting Classifier Results (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting):")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_voting):.4f}")
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred_voting))

The results are outstanding, better than with Random Forest alone ! This means that the voting method allows the three prediction models to work better together. We can try other Ensemble Learning methods to see if they work any better. Let's start with the hard-voting method, based upon majority-based aggregation.

In[54]:
voting_model_hard = VotingClassifier(estimators=[
    ('lr', logistic_model),
    ('rf', rf_model),
    ('xgb', xgb_model)
], voting='hard')

voting_model_hard.fit(X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced)

y_pred_voting_hard = voting_model_hard.predict(X_test)

print("Hard Voting Classifier Results (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting):")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_voting_hard):.4f}")
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred_voting_hard))

Hard Voting Classifier Results (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting):
Accuracy: 0.9925

Classification Report:
               precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.99      1.00      1.00       318
           1       0.99      0.98      0.98        81

    accuracy                           0.99       399
   macro avg       0.99      0.99      0.99       399
weighted avg       0.99      0.99      0.99       399

Here, we have a slightly worse global accuracy, but we have better recall. As recall focuses on the minority class (here, we want to minimize false positives), it's a very important indicator to take into account, as we have a majority class which fusses the accuracy. Basically, hard-voting is better for this dataset, as it is quite disequilibrated, and final results indicate that with hard-voting, we predict the 0 event correctly in 99% of cases and the 1 event in 99% of cases as well. Meanwhile, with soft voting, we predict the 1 event right in 100% of cases, but we're worse on the 0 event : when we perdict 0, we're right only in 98% of cases.

Now we're alright, For the next part let's use other ensemble learning techniques We can say we can predict a country's ability to more than 50% renewables share in energy quite well : using this ensemble voting technique, we can predict this right in 99.25% of cases. The results are slightly worse for both Random Forest and Gradient Boosting for events 0 and 1. Meanwhile, they are better for the Logistic Regression. A Logistic Regression model trained on balanced data can then be useful in an Ensemble Learning method. Although these results are more interesting than the ones we got with non-balanced data, we can try to enhance them with other data balancing methods. To try them faster, we can make a for loop and try all balancing methods that we can find, and compare the results then.

In[60]:
# Define balancing methods
balancing_methods = {
    "Random UnderSampler": RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42),
    "SMOTE": SMOTE(random_state=42),
    "Borderline-SMOTE": BorderlineSMOTE(random_state=42),
    "NearMiss": NearMiss(version=1),
    "SMOTEENN": SMOTEENN(random_state=42),
    "SMOTETomek": SMOTETomek(random_state=42),
    "Class Weights (Balanced)": "balanced",
    "Balanced Random Forest": BalancedRandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
    "Easy Ensemble": EasyEnsembleClassifier(random_state=42),
    "ADASYN": ADASYN(random_state=42),
}

# Define models
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42),
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42)
}

# Iterate through balancing methods
for method_name, method in balancing_methods.items():
    print(f"\n=== Balancing Method: {method_name} ===")
    try:
        if method_name in ["Balanced Random Forest", "Easy Ensemble"]:
            # For ensemble methods, directly use the method as a model
            method.fit(X_train, y_train)
            y_pred = method.predict(X_test)
            print(f"\nAccuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
            print("Classification Report:")
            print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
        elif method_name == "Class Weights (Balanced)":
            # Apply class weights directly in the models
            for model_name, model in models.items():
                if isinstance(model, (LogisticRegression, RandomForestClassifier)):
                    model.set_params(class_weight="balanced")
                model.fit(X_train, y_train)
                y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
                print(f"\nModel: {model_name}")
                print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
                print("Classification Report:")
                print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
        else:
            # Balance the training data for other methods
            X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced = method.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)
            for model_name, model in models.items():
                model.fit(X_train_balanced, y_train_balanced)
                y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
                print(f"\nModel: {model_name}")
                print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
                print("Classification Report:")
                print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error with method {method_name}: {e}")

weighted avg       0.98      0.98      0.98       265

Here, most methods don't work better than Gradient Boosting without SMOTE. The only balancing method giving better results is SMOTEENN, with a Logistic Regression model. The SMOTEENN method combines two techniques (SMOTE and ENN) to address class imbalance effectively. First, SMOTE generates synthetic samples for the minority class by interpolating between existing samples an their nearest neighbors, enhancing the representation of the minority class. Then, Edited Nearest Neighbors (ENN) cleans the dataset by removing samples from both classes that are misclassified by their k-nearest neighbors, reducing noise and overlap between classes. This combined approach balances the dataset while improving the decision boundaries for classification. SMOTEENN works particularly well here because as it removes samples near class boundaries (the ones prone to misclassification), it improves the separation between classes. This is particularly useful in contexts with overlapping features such as energy production and consumption, which may have ambiguous class boundaries. Energy-related data often exhibit non-linear relationships and noisy distributions due to differences between countries (e.g., industrialization, policies). SMOTEENN enhances the decision boundaries by balanacing the dataset while filtering out noisy examples, which ensures the model learns robust patterns instead of overfitting to noise. This is also why it works better with Logistic Regression when Logistic Regression is worse with most of other balancing methods. Logistic Regression works better when we have linear decision boundaries, which makes it work better when the oversampling step creates synthetic samples along linear interpolations between minority class points. These samples reinforce the linear reationship.

We can still enhance these results, adjusting the parameters of SMOTEENN. This time we'll use a grid search to look for the best hyperparameters.

In[61]:
# This time we'll use a Pipeline, a very used tool in Machine Learning.
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('smoteenn', SMOTEENN(
        smote=SMOTE(sampling_strategy=0.75, k_neighbors=5, random_state=42),
        enn=EditedNearestNeighbours(n_neighbors=5, sampling_strategy='majority')
    )),
    ('classifier', LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, random_state=42))
])

# Define parameter grid for optimization
param_grid = {
    'smoteenn__smote__k_neighbors': [3, 5, 7],
    'smoteenn__enn__n_neighbors': [3, 5, 7],
    'classifier__C': [0.1, 1, 10],
    'classifier__solver': ['lbfgs', 'liblinear'] }

# Perform grid search and show found parameters
grid_search = GridSearchCV(pipeline, param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=3, n_jobs=-1)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

# Evaluate and show the best parameters performance
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)
print("\nAccuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

Best Parameters: {'classifier__C': 0.1, 'classifier__solver': 'lbfgs', 'smoteenn__enn__n_neighbors': 5, 'smoteenn__smote__k_neighbors': 7}

Are Ensemble Learning methods better than using Logistic Regression on SMOTEENN-balanced data ?

Logistic Regression on SMOTEENN-balanced data gives good results, with .97 accuracy on the 0 event and .86 on the 1 event. Other methods have given acceptable results, it might be a good idea to combine them in Ensemble Learning. Moreover, some Ensemble Learning methods perform very well on inbalanced datasets. Let's implement these and then take a look at the results.

In[62]:
# We'll start with 2 methods we haven't used yet :
ensemble_methods = {
    "Balanced Random Forest": BalancedRandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, sampling_strategy="all", replacement=True, bootstrap=False),
    "Easy Ensemble": EasyEnsembleClassifier(random_state=42)
}

# Evaluate each ensemble method, using once again a for loop :
for method_name, model in ensemble_methods.items():
    print(f"\n=== Ensemble Method: {method_name} ===")
    try:
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
        print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
        print("Classification Report:")
        print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error with ensemble method {method_name}: {e}")

These 2 Ensemble Learning Methods produce worse results than the Logistic Regression. We can try to balance the data again and implement a voting method between the LR model and those methods.

In[63]:
smoteenn = SMOTEENN(
    smote=SMOTE(sampling_strategy=0.75, k_neighbors=7, random_state=42),  # Best k_neighbors
    enn=EditedNearestNeighbours(n_neighbors=5, sampling_strategy='majority'))  # Best n_neighbors
X_train_smoteenn, y_train_smoteenn = smoteenn.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Logistic Regression with best parameters
logistic_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, C=0.1, solver='lbfgs', random_state=42)  # Best parameters
logistic_model.fit(X_train_smoteenn, y_train_smoteenn)


# Combine Logistic Regression and Ensemble Models in a Voting Classifier
voting_ensemble = VotingClassifier(
    estimators=[
        ('logistic', logistic_model),
        ('balanced_rf', ensemble_methods["Balanced Random Forest"]),
        ('easy_ensemble', ensemble_methods["Easy Ensemble"])
    ],
    voting='soft')

# Train and evaluate the voting method
voting_ensemble.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_voting = voting_ensemble.predict(X_test)
print("\n=== Combined Voting Classifier ===")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_voting):.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_voting))

The results are still not better than Logistic Regression alone. Let's try with a model complementary to Logistic Regression : Logistic Regression is a linear model, so let's implement voting with models capturing non-linear relationships. Gradient Boosting, for example, can model non-linearities and interactions that Logistic Regression might miss.

In[64]:
logistic_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, C=0.1, solver='lbfgs', random_state=42)
logistic_model.fit(X_train_smoteenn, y_train_smoteenn)

# Train Gradient Boosting Classifier on SMOTEENN-balanced data
gb_model = GradientBoostingClassifier(n_estimators=100, learning_rate=0.1, max_depth=3, random_state=42)
gb_model.fit(X_train_smoteenn, y_train_smoteenn)

# Combine models in a Voting Classifier
voting_ensemble = VotingClassifier(
    estimators=[
        ('logistic', logistic_model),
        ('gradient_boosting', gb_model)
    ],
    voting='soft')

voting_ensemble.fit(X_train_smoteenn, y_train_smoteenn)
y_pred_voting = voting_ensemble.predict(X_test)
print("\n=== Combined Soft Voting Classifier ===")
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_voting):.4f}")
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred_voting))

# Evaluate the combined Voting Classifier

Hard-Voting method between logistic regression and gradient boosting on data balanced using SMOTEENN gives tremendous results ! There, we have a correct prediction 96.6% of the time : whern the model predicts the 1 one event, it's always right, and when it predicts 0 (the majority class, so the one we can afford to make errors with), it's right 97% of the time.

For the next stage of this project, we can try another strategy to predict whether or not a country has more than 90% low-carbon electricity percentage. Rather that making this a binary variable, we can try to predict directly the percentage using Deep Learning and compare the result.

Stage 3 : More improvements, more and more

In this stage we're supposed to add more improvements, using algorithms outside of the course (even Deep Learning ones). We will remain on the same problematic but will use several models to see which ones perform better, testing these with techniques such as pipelines and hyperparameters grid search.

The models we use here are Deep Neural Networks using libraries such as Keras and PyTorch, Regression Neural Network, and LSTM. Reasons why we choose those models are explained in the joint document.

In[66]:
# Let's start with getting back data, with low-carbon electricity percentage as Y.
features = ['population', 'gdp', 'electricity_generation', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'hydro_share_elec', 'renewables_share_energy', 'renewable_energy_percentage', 'hydro_share_energy',
            'low_carbon_share_energy', 'biofuel_share_energy', 'renewables_energy_per_capita', 'hydro_energy_per_capita', 'low_carbon_energy_per_capita', 'biofuel_cons_per_capita', 'hydro_elec_per_capita', 'renewables_elec_per_capita',
            'year', 'low_carbon_elec_per_capita', 'other_renewables_share_energy', 'other_renewables_share_elec', 'hydro_consumption', 'hydro_electricity', 'per_capita_electricity', 'gas_energy_per_capita']
X = energy_data[features]
y = energy_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']
X=X.dropna()
y=y.loc[X.index]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

We'll start with the most basic technique used in this part, Deep Neural Network. This technique is relevant when linear regression models' results can't progress anymore ; moreover, this method is more suitable for large-scale datasets such as our, at it captures better its complexity and shades. It also allows us to use regularization techniques unavailable in most regression techniques such as dropout to make the prediction model more robust. Optimizers and techniques like batch training also make this approach able to converge faster than trraditional gradient descent.

In[67]:
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Build the neural network
model = Sequential([
    Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],)),
    Dropout(0.2),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.2),
    Dense(16, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1, activation='linear')])

# Compile the modeel
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Train the model
history = model.fit(
    X_train_scaled, y_train,
    validation_split=0.2,
    epochs=100,
    batch_size=32,
    verbose=1)

# Now we evaluate the model
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled).flatten()
print("\n=== Evaluation ===")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")

Here, we use significantly more epochs than in the lesson ; we need it bcause we have significantly more data influencing our output. Having more epochs allows us to have more learning stabiliy and better capture complex relationships. We can see visually how useful it is by drawing a graph of the training and precision loss in function of the number of epochs :

In[68]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss', linestyle='--')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss (MSE)')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Here the validation and training loss converge together, meaning the model generalizes well to the test data.

Let's take a look at the predictions of the model !

This is not as good as the voter model. Let's try it with other hyperparameters ! Here we increased the number of neurons to 128 for a more complex feature extraction, increased dropout rate to 0.3 to further mitigate overfitting, increased the number of epochs to 150 to allow for more training iterations.

In[72]:
# Build the neural network
model = Sequential([
    Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],)), 
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(1, activation='linear')])

# Compile the modele
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
history = model.fit(
    X_train_scaled, y_train,
    validation_split=0.2,
    epochs=150,
    batch_size=32,
    verbose=1)

# Time to evaluate !
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled).flatten()
print("\n=== Evaluation ===")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")

# Now we apply the same method as before to create a binary column and generate a classification report.
predictions_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'True Value': y_test.values,
    'Predicted Value': y_pred
}, index=X_test.index)

X_test_with_features = pd.DataFrame(X_test, columns=X.columns, index=X_test.index)
predictions_df = pd.concat([
    X_test_with_features,
    pd.DataFrame({'True Value': y_test.values, 'Predicted Value': y_pred}, index=X_test.index)], axis=1)

predictions_df['Actual > 90%'] = (predictions_df['True Value'] > 90).astype(int)
predictions_df['Predicted > 90%'] = (predictions_df['Predicted Value'] > 90).astype(int)

# Time for the  classification report
report = classification_report(predictions_df['Actual > 90%'], predictions_df['Predicted > 90%'], target_names=['<=90%', '>90%'])
print("\n=== Classification Report ===")
print(report)

In[74]:
optimizers = [
    ('SGD', SGD(learning_rate=0.01, clipnorm=1.0)),
    ('RMSprop', RMSprop(learning_rate=0.001)),
    ('Adagrad', Adagrad(learning_rate=0.01)),
    ('Adam', Adam(learning_rate=0.001))]

results = {}
for name, optimizer in optimizers:
    model = Sequential([
        Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],)),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(64, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(32, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(1, activation='linear')
    ])
    
    # Compile the model with the current optimizer
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
    
    print(f"\n=== Training with {name} Optimizer ===")
    
    # Train th model
    history = model.fit(
        X_train_scaled, y_train,
        validation_split=0.2,
        epochs=50,  # Reduced epochs for quicker testing
        batch_size=32,
        verbose=1
    )
    
    # Evaluate the model using MSE and MAE, which are more currently used for Deep Neural Networks.
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled).flatten()
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    results[name] = {'MAE': mae, 'MSE': mse}
    print(f"\nOptimizer: {name}")
    print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mae:.4f}")
    print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.4f}")

# Print summarized results
print("\n\n\n\n\=== Optimizer Comparison Results ===")
for name, metrics in results.items():
    print(f"{name}: MAE = {metrics['MAE']:.4f}, MSE = {metrics['MSE']:.4f}")

# Build the neural network
model = Sequential([
    Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],)), 
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(32, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(1, activation='linear')])

# Compile the modele
model.compile(optimizer=RMSprop(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])
history = model.fit(
    X_train_scaled, y_train,
    validation_split=0.2,
    epochs=150,
    batch_size=32,
    verbose=1)

# Time to evaluate !
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_scaled).flatten()
print("\n=== Evaluation ===")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")

# Now we apply the same method as before to create a binary column and generate a classification report.
predictions_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'True Value': y_test.values,
    'Predicted Value': y_pred
}, index=X_test.index)

X_test_with_features = pd.DataFrame(X_test, columns=X.columns, index=X_test.index)
predictions_df = pd.concat([
    X_test_with_features,
    pd.DataFrame({'True Value': y_test.values, 'Predicted Value': y_pred}, index=X_test.index)], axis=1)

predictions_df['Actual > 90%'] = (predictions_df['True Value'] > 90).astype(int)
predictions_df['Predicted > 90%'] = (predictions_df['Predicted Value'] > 90).astype(int)

# Time for the  classification report
report = classification_report(predictions_df['Actual > 90%'], predictions_df['Predicted > 90%'], target_names=['<=90%', '>90%'])
print("\n=== Classification Report ===")
print(report)

The results are still not very satisfying when compared to the voting method and XGBoost. Let's try using another library, PyTorch. Moreover, PyTorch is generally easier and faster to set up and experiment with, and gives more control over architecture and training process. The downside is that it gives less control over low-level training details. It's noticeably very useful for custom training loops such as Pipelines and Grid Search.

In[76]:
# The first step is to convert data to PyTorch tensors
X_train_tensor = torch.tensor(X_train_scaled, dtype=torch.float32)
y_train_tensor = torch.tensor(y_train.values, dtype=torch.float32).unsqueeze(1)
X_test_tensor = torch.tensor(X_test_scaled, dtype=torch.float32)
y_test_tensor = torch.tensor(y_test.values, dtype=torch.float32).unsqueeze(1)

# Then we define the neural network architecture
class RegressionNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(RegressionNN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(X_train_tensor.shape[1], 128)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(128, 64)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(64, 32)
        self.fc4 = nn.Linear(32, 1)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.3)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.relu(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.relu(self.fc3(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.fc4(x)
        return x

# Initialize the model, loss function, and optimizer
model = RegressionNN()
criterion = nn.MSELoss()  # We'll be looking to try to minimize MSE to start, as it's the most widely used indicator for  Neural networks. 
optimizer = optim.RMSprop(model.parameters(), lr=0.001)

# Training loop
num_epochs = 150
batch_size = 32
train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
    list(zip(X_train_tensor, y_train_tensor)), batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True)

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    model.train()
    epoch_loss = 0
    for batch_X, batch_y in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        predictions = model(batch_X)
        loss = criterion(predictions, batch_y)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        epoch_loss += loss.item()
    if (epoch + 1) % 10 == 0:
        print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{num_epochs}, Loss: {epoch_loss/len(train_loader):.4f}")

# Evaluation
model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    y_pred_tensor = model(X_test_tensor).squeeze()
    y_pred = y_pred_tensor.numpy()
print("\n=== Evaluation ===")
print(f"Mean Absolute Error (MAE): {mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")
print(f"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred):.4f}")

The results look the same than with Keras, but we used rather arbitrary hyperparameters. It's a good sign, we can probably get getter results adjusting the hyperparameters ! We'll look for them using a Grid Search :

In[77]:
# We have to write the class RegressionNN over again for it to adapt each time to the hyperparameters being passed to it.
class RegressionNN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_sizes, dropout_rate):
        super(RegressionNN, self).__init__()
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_sizes[0])
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(hidden_sizes[0], hidden_sizes[1])
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(hidden_sizes[1], hidden_sizes[2])
        self.fc4 = nn.Linear(hidden_sizes[2], 1)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(dropout_rate)
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.relu(self.fc2(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.relu(self.fc3(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.fc4(x)
        return x


# Hyperparameter space
learning_rates = [0.01, 0.001, 0.0001]
batch_sizes = [16, 32, 64]
dropout_rates = [0.1, 0.3, 0.5]
hidden_layer_configs = [
    [128, 64, 32],  # 3 hidden layers
    [256, 128, 64]  # Larger hidden layers
]
num_epochs = 50  # Fixed for comparison, we can put more when training the chosen model, once we know the best hyperparameters for sure

# Now let's perform the grid searh
results = {}
for lr, batch_size, dropout_rate, hidden_sizes in itertools.product(
    learning_rates, batch_sizes, dropout_rates, hidden_layer_configs
):
    print(f"Testing configuration: LR={lr}, Batch Size={batch_size}, Dropout={dropout_rate}, Layers={hidden_sizes}")
    
    # Prepare the data loader
    train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
        list(zip(X_train_tensor, y_train_tensor)), batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True
    )
    
    # Initialize model, loss function, and optimizer
    model = RegressionNN(input_size=X_train_tensor.shape[1], hidden_sizes=hidden_sizes, dropout_rate=dropout_rate)
    criterion = nn.MSELoss()
    optimizer = optim.RMSprop(model.parameters(), lr=lr)
    
    # Train the model
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        epoch_loss = 0
        for batch_X, batch_y in train_loader:
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            predictions = model(batch_X)
            loss = criterion(predictions, batch_y)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            epoch_loss += loss.item()
    
    # Evaluate the model
    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        y_pred_tensor = model(X_test_tensor).squeeze()
        y_pred = y_pred_tensor.numpy()
    
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    results[(lr, batch_size, dropout_rate, tuple(hidden_sizes))] = (mae, mse)
    print(f"MAE: {mae:.4f}, MSE: {mse:.4f}")

# Find the best configuration
best_config = min(results, key=lambda x: results[x][1])  # Minimize MSE
print("\nBest Configuration:")
print(f"LR={best_config[0]}, Batch Size={best_config[1]}, Dropout={best_config[2]}, Layers={best_config[3]}")
print(f"MAE: {results[best_config][0]:.4f}, MSE: {results[best_config][1]:.4f}")

# Retrain the model with the best hyperparameters
best_lr, best_batch_size, best_dropout_rate, best_hidden_sizes = best_config

# Prepare the data loader with the best batch size
train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
    list(zip(X_train_tensor, y_train_tensor)), batch_size=best_batch_size, shuffle=True)

# Initialize the model, loss function, optimizer as before
best_model = RegressionNN(
    input_size=X_train_tensor.shape[1],
    hidden_sizes=best_hidden_sizes,
    dropout_rate=best_dropout_rate)
criterion = nn.MSELoss()
optimizer = optim.RMSprop(best_model.parameters(), lr=best_lr)
num_epochs=150 # This time we take a higher number of epochs to get more precise results.

# Train the best model
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    best_model.train()
    epoch_loss = 0
    for batch_X, batch_y in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        predictions = best_model(batch_X)
        loss = criterion(predictions, batch_y)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        epoch_loss += loss.item()

# Save predictions with the best model
best_model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    best_y_pred_tensor = best_model(X_test_tensor).squeeze()
    best_y_pred = best_y_pred_tensor.numpy()

# Now, `best_y_pred` contains the predictions from the model trained with the best hyperparameters

# Create a DataFrame to store predictions and true values

    'True Value': y_test,
    'Predicted Value': best_y_pred
}, index=X_test.index)

We can get better results. The loop has been trained to look for the smaller MSE and not the best deal on the classification report. It would probably be a better idea to try to get the best f1-score, as we're working on imbalanced data. This time we'll do it over again, but put the function to predict if a country has more or less than 90% low-carbon energy in the loop and try to get the best f1-score instead.

In[79]:
# Initialize variables for the best model and results
best_f1 = -float('inf')  # Start with the lowest possible F1 score
best_model_state = None
best_y_pred = None
best_config = None

# Grid search
for lr, batch_size, dropout_rate, hidden_sizes in itertools.product(
    learning_rates, batch_sizes, dropout_rates, hidden_layer_configs
):
    print(f"Testing configuration: LR={lr}, Batch Size={batch_size}, Dropout={dropout_rate}, Layers={hidden_sizes}")
    
    # Prepare the data loader
    train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(
        list(zip(X_train_tensor, y_train_tensor)), batch_size=batch_size, shuffle=True
    )
    
    # Initialize model, loss function, and optimizer
    model = RegressionNN(input_size=X_train_tensor.shape[1], hidden_sizes=hidden_sizes, dropout_rate=dropout_rate)
    criterion = nn.MSELoss()
    optimizer = optim.RMSprop(model.parameters(), lr=lr)
    
    # Train the model
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        for batch_X, batch_y in train_loader:
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            predictions = model(batch_X)
            loss = criterion(predictions, batch_y)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
    
    # Evaluate the model
    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        y_pred_tensor = model(X_test_tensor).squeeze()
        y_pred = y_pred_tensor.numpy()
    
    # Binary classification columns for actual and predicted values
    threshold = 90  # Define threshold
    y_test_binary = (y_test > threshold).astype(int)
    y_pred_binary = (y_pred > threshold).astype(int)
    
    # Calculate F1-score
    f1 = f1_score(y_test_binary, y_pred_binary)
    print(f"F1-Score: {f1:.4f}")

    # Update the best model if F1-score is higher
    if f1 > best_f1:
        best_f1 = f1
        best_model_state = model.state_dict()  # Save model state
        best_y_pred = y_pred  # Save predictions
        best_config = (lr, batch_size, dropout_rate, hidden_sizes)
        print(f"New best model found! F1-Score: {best_f1:.4f}")

print("\nBest Configuration:")
print(f"LR={best_config[0]}, Batch Size={best_config[1]}, Dropout={best_config[2]}, Layers={best_config[3]}")
print(f"F1-Score = {best_f1:.4f}")

Another model : LSTM

For this last part, we will implement an LSTM model. Explained further in the joint explicative document, it is a type of Recurrent Neural Network dessigned to learn and make predictions from sequential data. Here each country or area of the world has several years of data and we're trying to study the dynamics one country can have, so basing this on previous years as sequential data, rather than considering everything independent and considering all countries have identics dynamics, is a good idea.

A very important part of how one uses LSTM is the choice of the time step. Assuming the whole dataset is composed of smaller subsets of data, each being taken over a given time, time step would be said given time. To identify the time step we should use here, we shall look at the time spans for each country in the dataset.

In[81]:
# Count the number of unique years of data available for each country
features = ['country', 'year', 'population', 'gdp', 'electricity_generation', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'hydro_share_elec', 'renewables_share_energy', 'renewable_energy_percentage', 'hydro_share_energy',
            'low_carbon_share_energy', 'biofuel_share_energy', 'renewables_energy_per_capita', 'hydro_energy_per_capita', 'low_carbon_energy_per_capita', 'biofuel_cons_per_capita', 'hydro_elec_per_capita', 'renewables_elec_per_capita',

All countries taken into account to train our model will need to have the same number of years of data available ; this means, if a country has more, we'll cut some years to get the same number as the threshold we will have defined. If a country has less years of data available, we won't take it into account. We need to define the threshold accordingly to get the maximum data without losing too much information because we'd have too few years on record. On this graph, we can see that 15 years looks like a good threshold. Let's format data this way :

Now we can use LSTM with a time step of 15.

In[83]:
# To use LSTM, we need to normalize the data.
features_ = features[1:-1]
X = energy_data[features_]
y = energy_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']
X=X.dropna()
y=y.loc[X.index]

# Normalize data
scaler_X = MinMaxScaler()
scaler_y = MinMaxScaler()
X_scaled = scaler_X.fit_transform(X)
y_scaled = scaler_y.fit_transform(y.values.reshape(-1, 1))

# Convert data to sequences for LSTM
def create_sequences(X, y, time_steps):
    X_seq, y_seq = [], []
    for i in range(len(X) - time_steps):
        X_seq.append(X[i:i+time_steps, :])
        y_seq.append(y[i+time_steps])
    return np.array(X_seq), np.array(y_seq)

time_steps = 15

X_seq, y_seq = create_sequences(X_scaled, y_scaled, time_steps)

# While using LSTM, we split data ONCE we have created the sequences.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_seq, y_seq, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
In[84]:
# Build the LSTM model
model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(50, activation='relu', input_shape=(time_steps, X_train.shape[2])))
model.add(Dense(1))  # Output layer

# Compile and train the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), verbose=1)

# Calculate RMSE or other metrics
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_rescaled, y_pred_rescaled))
print(f"RMSE: {rmse}")

13/13  0s 9ms/step

RMSE is 11.8, which is quite high for a range of 100 (>10%). This is because we don't have enough data. We can confirm this by comparing Test RMSE with training RMSE.

In[86]:
# Predict on training data
y_train_pred = model.predict(X_train)

# Rescale predictions and actual values back to original scale
y_train_pred_rescaled = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_train_pred)
y_train_rescaled = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_train)

rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_rescaled, y_train_pred_rescaled))
print(f"Training RMSE: {rmse_train}")


# Predict on test data
y_test_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Rescale predictions and actual values back to original scale
y_test_pred_rescaled = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_test_pred)
y_test_rescaled = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_test)

# Calculate RMSE for test data
rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_rescaled, y_test_pred_rescaled))

29/29  0s 2ms/step 
Training RMSE: 7.489795986628153
13/13  0s 2ms/step 
Test RMSE: 11.721722967359494

We can see on the graph that Test RMSE is nearly 1.5x the value of training RMSE. This, in our case, indicates overfitting : due to the low number of data, the models overfits on the training data but doesn't generalize well. We had to suppress too much data because of null values in our dataset. LSTM is probably not adaptated to data with this shape. We can still try to enhance hyperparameters to see if it makes things better, as 11.8 is not great but not catastrophic either.

In[87]:
# hyperparameters to tune
neurons = 150
dropouts = [0.0, 0.2, 0.5]
learning_rates = [0.001, 0.01]
batch_sizes = [16, 32]
time_steps_options = [5, 10, 20]

# Function to create sequences
def create_sequences(X, y, time_steps):
    X_seq, y_seq = [], []
    for i in range(len(X) - time_steps):
        X_seq.append(X[i:i + time_steps, :])
        y_seq.append(y[i + time_steps])
    return np.array(X_seq), np.array(y_seq)


results = []
# Iterate through all parameter combinations
for dropout_, lr_, batch_size_, time_steps_ in itertools.product(dropouts, learning_rates, batch_sizes, time_steps_options):
    
    # Prepare data with the current time_steps
    X_seq, y_seq = create_sequences(X_scaled, y_scaled, time_steps_)
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_seq, y_seq, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)
    
    # Build the model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(LSTM(neurons, activation='tanh', input_shape=(time_steps_, X_train.shape[2])))
    if dropout_ > 0.0:
        model.add(Dropout(dropout_))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    
    # Compile the model
    optimizer = Adam(learning_rate=lr_)
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss='mse')
    
    # Train the model
    history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=batch_size_, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), verbose=0)
    
    # Predict & calculate RMSE
    y_train_pred = scaler_y.inverse_transform(model.predict(X_train))
    y_train_actual = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_train)
    y_test_pred = scaler_y.inverse_transform(model.predict(X_test))
    y_test_actual = scaler_y.inverse_transform(y_test)
    
    rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_actual, y_train_pred))
    rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_actual, y_test_pred))
    
    # Store the results
    results.append({
        'neurons': neurons,
        'dropout': dropout_,
        'learning_rate': lr_,
        'batch_size': batch_size_,
        'time_steps': time_steps_,
        'rmse_train': rmse_train,
        'rmse_test': rmse_test
    })
    
    print(f"Done: dropout={dropout_}, lr={lr_}, batch_size={batch_size_}, time_steps={time_steps_}")

# Convert results to a DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)
results_df = results_df.sort_values(by='rmse_test')

# Display results and show the top configs to draw conclusions
print("LSTM Hyperparameter Tuning Results:")
print(results_df.head(10))

The results are way better, comparable to what we got with the hard-voting method between XGBoost and Logistic Regression ! We can notice it's still not better than the Voting model, though.

Project Conclusion

LTSM has finally been able to work quite correctly, and it would be even better with more data. Maybe it would be better, but for now the Voting method was the one that worked best. This also tells us that the more "complicated" and sophisticated model isn't always the better solution ; here, we had satisfying results with XGBoost, and the best results we got were with an Ensemble Learning technique adressed between XGBoost and a Linear Regression. We had worse results with a Deep Neural network, even when optimizing the hyperparameters. It was worth trying it and very important to try to adjust hyperparameters.

To sum eveything up, if we want to predict a country's ability to use low-carbon and renewable energies based on diverse data, as all of this data is closely related, we don't need to dig deep in Neural Network techniques. Simple regressions and Gradient Boost techniques give satisfying techniques.

Addendum

Separating countries in only 2 categories can make us short of information when we'll need these predictions. A political advisor or decision-maker, for example, could need a more refined report. That's the occasion for us to implement technical solutions we never got the chance to implement here, but that are often major parts of Machine Learning courses : classification problems. We will also take the occasion to use PCA, that we've a bit underused, which is a very good solution to limit the resources needed to execute a code, and is fitting our situation : PCA works better when several segments of data are highly correlated, and we have this here.

Here, we will start with a simple Random Forest Classifier, which will allow us to implement PCA a first time.

In[90]:
features = ['population', 'gdp', 'electricity_generation', 'fossil_fuel_consumption', 'hydro_share_elec', 'renewables_share_energy', 'renewable_energy_percentage', 'hydro_share_energy',
            'low_carbon_share_energy', 'biofuel_share_energy', 'renewables_energy_per_capita', 'hydro_energy_per_capita', 'low_carbon_energy_per_capita', 'biofuel_cons_per_capita', 'hydro_elec_per_capita', 'renewables_elec_per_capita',
            'year', 'low_carbon_elec_per_capita', 'other_renewables_share_energy', 'other_renewables_share_elec', 'hydro_consumption', 'hydro_electricity', 'per_capita_electricity', 'gas_energy_per_capita']

filtered_data = energy_data[features + ['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']].dropna()
X = filtered_data[features]
y = filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']

# Binning the target variable into 3 classes
bins = [0, 30, 60, 100]
labels = ['Low', 'Medium', 'High']
y_binned = pd.cut(y, bins=bins, labels=labels)

# Ensure no NaN values in features or target
X_cleaned = X.loc[y_binned.dropna().index]
y_binned_cleaned = y_binned.dropna()
X_cleaned = X_cleaned.dropna()
y_binned_cleaned = y_binned_cleaned.loc[X_cleaned.index]

# Standardize features and apply PCA
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_cleaned)
pca = PCA(n_components=0.95)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)

# Split the data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_pca, y_binned_cleaned, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Train a Random Forest Classifier, a basic choice for a categorical prevision.
clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
classification_report_result = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, output_dict=True)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)

# Display the results
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy}")

results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Actual': y_test.values,
    'Predicted': y_pred})

# Calculate probabilities for each class
probabilities = clf.predict_proba(X_test)
class_labels = clf.classes_  # Get the class labels

# Add probabilities to the results DataFrame
for idx, label in enumerate(class_labels):
    results_df[f'Probability_{label}'] = probabilities[:, idx]

# Include a few principal components for context
components_to_display = 3
for i in range(components_to_display):
    results_df[f'PC{i + 1}'] = X_test[:, i]

# Define a function to apply conditional formatting
def highlight_row(row):
    if row['Actual'] == row['Predicted']:
        return ['background-color: lightgreen'] * len(row)
    else:
        return ['background-color: lightcoral'] * len(row)

# Display PCA components for context
print("PCA Components:")
pca_components = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_, columns=X_cleaned.columns, 
                              index=[f'PC{i+1}' for i in range(pca.components_.shape[0])])
display(pca_components)

# Apply conditional formatting and display the styled DataFrame
styled_df = results_df.head(10).style.apply(highlight_row, axis=1)
display(styled_df)

In[92]:
# We'll use a pipeline to see if results are better with PCA with other models.

# First we define the models to test
models = {
    "Logistic Regression": LogisticRegression(random_state=42, max_iter=500),
    "SVM": SVC(random_state=42),
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42),
    "k-Nearest Neighbors": KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5)}

# Iterate over models and evaluate each
results = {}
for model_name, model in models.items():
    # Train the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Predict on the test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Store accuracy and classification report
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    classification_report_result = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, output_dict=True)
    
    # Save the results
    results[model_name] = {
        "Accuracy": accuracy,
        "Classification Report": classification_report_result,
        "Predictions": pd.DataFrame({
            'Actual': y_test.values,
            'Predicted': y_pred})}

# Display results
for model_name, result in results.items():
    print(f"Model: {model_name}")
    print(f"Accuracy: {result['Accuracy']:.2f}")
    display(pd.DataFrame(result['Classification Report']).transpose())

We can also try a Sequential model using the keras library, as we did in the end of Stage 3. For that, we will need to use one-hot encoding.

In[93]:
# One-hot encode the target variable
encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False)
y_train_encoded = encoder.fit_transform(y_train.values.reshape(-1, 1))
y_test_encoded = encoder.transform(y_test.values.reshape(-1, 1))

# Define the Sequential Keras model
model = Sequential([
    Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],)),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.3),
    Dense(y_train_encoded.shape[1], activation='softmax')])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
history = model.fit(X_train, y_train_encoded, epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.2, verbose=1)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred_encoded = model.predict(X_test)
y_pred = encoder.inverse_transform(y_pred_encoded)  # Decode one-hot predictions

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_report_result = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, output_dict=True)

# Combine predictions and actual labels into a DataFrame
results_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Actual': y_test.values,
    'Predicted': y_pred.flatten()})


styled_df = results_df.head(10).style.apply(highlight_row, axis=1)
display(pd.DataFrame(classification_report_result).transpose())
display(styled_df)

The results don't change much. Once more, Neural Networks from the Keras library don't add much value compared to more basic models on this dataset.

Now, we can also take an interest in whether we enhance these when we're not using PCA. Do we have more precise data ? Does the model understand more information ? Or does it learn noise, meaning that PCA is energetically economic but also a good tool to learn and avoid overfitting ?

In[94]:
# Now, we try with the models that worked better but without PCA
filtered_data = energy_data[features + ['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']].dropna()

# Separate features and target
X = filtered_data[features]
y = filtered_data['low_carbon_electricity_percentage']

# Ensure no NaN values in features or target
X_cleaned = X.loc[y_binned.dropna().index]
y_binned_cleaned = y_binned.dropna()
X_cleaned = X_cleaned.dropna()
y_binned_cleaned = y_binned_cleaned.loc[X_cleaned.index]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_pca, y_binned_cleaned, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Standardize the features (skip PCA)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Define models
models = {
    "Gradient Boosting": GradientBoostingClassifier(random_state=42),
    "k-Nearest Neighbors": KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=5),
    "Random Forest": RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
}

# Train and evaluate each model
results = []

for model_name, model in models.items():
    # Train the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Predict on the test set
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Evaluate the model
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    classification_report_result = classification_report(y_test, y_pred, output_dict=True)
    f1_macro = classification_report_result['macro avg']['f1-score']
    f1_weighted = classification_report_result['weighted avg']['f1-score']
    
    # Store and display results
    results.append({
        "Model": model_name,
        "Accuracy": accuracy,
        "F1-Score (Macro)": f1_macro,
        "F1-Score (Weighted)": f1_weighted
    })

    print(f"Model: {model_name}")
    print(f"Accuracy: {result['Accuracy']:.2f}")
    print(f"F1-Score (Macro): {f1_macro:.2f}")
    print(f"F1-Score (Weighted): {f1_weighted:.2f}")
    display(pd.DataFrame(result['Classification Report']).transpose())

    styled_predictions = result['Predictions'].head(10).style.apply(highlight_row, axis=1)
    print(f"Predictions for {model_name}:")
    display(styled_predictions)

Model: Gradient Boosting

All models have comparable accuracy and F1-Scores to the same prediction with PCA, which confirms that this process is very relevant with this data. The only model to lose a bit of information (3%, which is widely acceptable) is the Random Forest. The pace at which these cells run also tells us a lot about how useful PCA, the last major part if the course displayed here, can be.
